DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(86)90011-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387886900118
AB  - An ‘interim sale’ is a sale undertaken with the intention of buying back the same good in the near future. Interim transactions play a prominent role in several markets and they tend to generate multiple equilibria. Such markets can get caught at a low-turnover equilibrium. It is alleged that in many LDCs the market for buying and selling land is extremely inactive. An interim-transactions model is constructed to explain this phenomenon. Wider issues in land markets, including distress sales, are analysed as well. The model is applied also to labour-tying and seasonality in backward agriculture.
