DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(86)90010-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387886900106
AB  - This study does not confirm the hypothesis that foreign firms are the most capital intensive in the developing countries, when their capital-labour ratios are compared with those of private local, mixed private local-foreign, mixed state-foreign, and state owned firms in Ghana (1970). The data rather rank the state sector as the most capital intensive, and foreign firms as more capital intensive than private local and mixed private firms. The results may be explained by the types of incentives the firms received. These results are not interpreted as confirming Pack's contra-hypothesis that foreign firms would be the least capital intensive in the LDCs.
